The paper proposes a framework for unsupervised domain adaptation using adversarial discriminative methods. This involves aligning the distribution of the source encoder posteriors to the source domain, and regularizing the discriminator as a denoising autoencoder. The paper uses standard datasets like MNIST, USPS, SVHN, MNIST-M and Office-31 to validate the framework. Given the focus on machine learning and computer vision techniques, as well as the use of standard datasets, the most likely sub-categories are cs.LG (Machine Learning), cs.CV (Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition), cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence), cs.CL (Computation and Language), and cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing).
